  <body>
    <div rend="parallel">
      <lg xml:id="MuTA93">
<l>niṉaittulaki lārteḷivār nīṇṭa tirumā</l>
<l>laṉaittulaku muḷḷoṭukki yāṉmēṟ – kaṉaittulavu</l>
<l>veḷḷattōr piḷḷaiyāy meḷḷat tuyiṉṟāṉai</l>
<l>yuḷḷattē vaineñcē yuyttu</l>
      </lg>
      <lg xml:lang="en">
<l>Who are those in the world who understand [him] by thought? Tirumāl</l>
<l>who became tall, him who, keeping the whole world inside [himself], as a child</l> 
<l>on the banyan [leaf] in the roaring, roiling sea, slept softly,</l>
<l>put [him] directly<note xml:lang="en" place="foot" note.>Both here and at the beginning of the next verse I suggest taking uyttu as an adverb, but it could also be read as a first imperative: “direct [and] put [him] inside, o heart.”</note> inside [yourself], o heart.</l>
      </lg>
    </div>
  </body>
